          "body": "Rechab and Baanah present the head to David with a theological claim: 'thus the LORD has given my lord the king vengeance this day on Saul and his descendants.' The logic seemed sound to them: David was God's anointed; Ish-bosheth was his enemy; therefore killing Ish-bosheth must be God's will. This is the oldest and most persistent error in the theology of political violence — equating the outcome one desires with the will of the God one nominally serves. The murderers are not irreligious; they are wrongly religious. They have used God's name to sanctify their own opportunism. Calvin observes that 'the wicked are always ready to transfer to God the blame for their crimes when they believe it will serve their interest.' David's response (4:9) is a masterclass in theological correction: he does not debate whether God has purposes in Ish-bosheth's death; he insists that the living God who redeems does not need treachery as His instrument, and that the credit men assign to divine providence for their crimes does not remove the blood from their hands."
