        "range": "4:2-4",
        "excerpt": "Saul's son had two men who were commanders of bands: the name of the one was Baanah and the name of the other Rechab, sons of Rimmon the Beerothite, of the sons of Benjamin.",
        "body": "The narrator identifies the murderers with unusual genealogical specificity, and the specificity is itself the argument. Rechab and Baanah are Benjaminites — the tribe of Saul himself. They should have been Ish-bosheth's most reliable loyalists. They are officers in his own army (*sarei gedudim* — commanders of raiding bands), men with access to the king's household. The very ones positioned to protect him are the ones who will kill him.\n\nThe Beeroth detail (4:2-3) is not historical filler. Beeroth was one of the four Gibeonite cities that Israel had sworn by covenant not to harm (Josh 9:17). Saul had violated that covenant by massacring the Gibeonites (2 Sam 21:1-2 — a fact whose significance emerges later in the book). The Beerothites fled to Gittaim and lived as resident aliens. Their displacement signals that the covenant violations of the Saulide regime had created a class of displaced persons within Benjamin's own territory — a detail that quietly indicts the house of Saul again, and perhaps explains why men with tenuous tribal loyalty might betray their king.\n\nThe Mephibosheth parenthesis (4:4) interrupts the narrative of the assassination precisely to reorient the reader. As the house of Saul is about to suffer its terminal blow, the narrator ensures we know that one heir of covenant significance remains — Jonathan's son, five years old when he fell and became lame, now hidden and helpless. Two things are signaled simultaneously: the dynasty is collapsing, and the covenant is not. The child named Mephibosheth ('from the mouth of shame' — a scribal substitute for Merib-baal, 'contender with Baal,' 1 Chron 8:34) will not be erased. David will find him in chapter 9 and honor the oath sworn to his father.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Sarei gedudim* (commanders of raiding bands) — *gedud* denotes a raiding or marauding unit, irregular military force. *Nakheh raglayim* (lame in his feet) — *nakheh* means 'stricken,' carrying connotations of affliction by external force. *Pasach* (became lame) — to limp, to be lame; the same root used of the limping prophets of Baal in 1 Kgs 18:21 (the people 'limping between two opinions')."
