        "excerpt": "They came to the middle of the house as if to get wheat, and they struck him in the belly; and Rechab and Baanah his brother escaped.",
        "body": "The narrative pacing of verses 5-7 is deliberate and reveals the narrator's moral perspective. He traces every step of the assassination: the time (midday heat), the pretense (collecting wheat — a domestic provisioning task), the penetration (to the interior of the house), the act (struck him in the belly), the escape (slipped away), the full account repeated in verse 7 with additional detail (bedroom, bed, beheading, departure through the night). The doubling of the account is a narrative technique that forces the reader to see the act twice — to absorb fully what was done.\n\nThe midday setting is important. Ancient Near Eastern society organized the day around the morning and evening work periods; midday was rest time. The household's defenses were at their lowest. Guards were inattentive. The king was alone in his bedroom — the most private and protected space in the house. To enter that space under a domestic pretense and kill the sleeping king is an act of maximum violation: it corrupts the categories of house (safety), bed (rest), midday (peace), and domestic provision (wheat). Everything that should signal security is turned into a weapon.\n\nThe beheading (4:7) crosses a further threshold. Decapitation of an enemy was a recognized act of trophy warfare (cf. Goliath, 1 Sam 17:54; Saul, 1 Sam 31:9), but here it transforms a murder into a political presentation. The head becomes a portable proof of deed, a credential for the reward Rechab and Baanah expect to collect. Their all-night journey through the Arabah — the desolate Jordan rift valley — has the character of guilty haste: they need to reach David before anyone else does, and before the implications of what they have done can catch up with them.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chomesh* (belly, v.6) — the midsection, occasionally translated 'fifth rib' in older versions; the mortal blow. *Malat* (slipped away, v.6) — to escape, to slip free, the same word used of the survivor who brings bad news (1 Sam 4:10). *Laylah* (night, v.7) — their journey through the Arabah all night underlines the urgency of guilt, not the confidence of righteousness."
