        "excerpt": "Behold, the head of Ish-bosheth the son of Saul, your enemy, who sought your life; thus the Lord has given my lord the king vengeance this day on Saul and his descendants.",
        "body": "The speech of Rechab and Baanah is a masterwork of self-serving theology. They invoke the LORD's name (4:8), they use covenant language ('my lord the king'), they invoke the concept of divine vengeance (*neqamah*), and they frame the murder within a narrative of divinely warranted justice. Every element is designed to present murder as ministry.\n\nTheir argument has three moves: (1) Ish-bosheth was your enemy who sought your life — establishing him as a legitimate target. (2) Therefore the LORD has given you vengeance — attributing the act to divine agency. (3) The vengeance extends to Saul and his descendants — situating the act within the sweep of God's rejection of Saul's dynasty. The argument is coherent in its own terms. It is also completely false.\n\nThe theological error is not that God had no purposes in the end of Ish-bosheth's reign — clearly He did, since Ish-bosheth's death opens the way for the united kingdom. The error is the identification of God's purposes with the murderers' methods. God's purposes may be served by events He did not prescribe and would not sanction. Rechab and Baanah commit what Keller might call the 'moralization of violence' — the reduction of a theological conviction ('God is on our side') to a license for whatever action that conviction might seem to endorse. David's response rejects the inference absolutely without denying God's sovereignty over the outcome.\n\nIt is worth noting that Ish-bosheth had in fact made David's life difficult — Abner's war had cost lives on both sides (2 Sam 2:17-32). But David had never once moved against Saul's house directly, having consistently maintained that the LORD's anointed is the LORD's to remove (1 Sam 24:6; 26:9-11). That consistent theology is not abandoned when it becomes politically convenient to abandon it.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Neqamah* (vengeance) — retributive justice, belonging properly to God (Deut 32:35, 'Vengeance is Mine'). The murderers appropriate divine prerogative as their own act. *Zera* (offspring, descendants) — the claim that the murder settles accounts with Saul's whole line is overreach; David will honor Mephibosheth (ch. 9) and refuse to treat the dynasty as cursed (2 Sam 9:3)."
